I updated the spec and addressed various concerns around the topics discussed during the Yoga PTG (a word of thanks to the Nova core developers for provided feedback).

https://etherpad.opendev.org/p/nova-yoga-ptg#L559

Namely:

* Upgrade-related:
  * Nova compute service versions;
  * Neutron upgrade considerations;
* Scheduling-related:
  * Described the prefilter to be implemented based on a new compute capability (relevant os-traits change will be raised in due course);
* Instance lifecycle operations and API stubs;
  * Described the operations that will raise API errors. I may revisit this list after some more investigation but for now the list is as in the uploaded change;
* Neutron proposal status:
  * Added a note about the RFE being approved already (the spec is being reviewed).

Other changes:

* Changed the wording regarding PCI VPD serial number extraction since we no longer need to handle that in Nova and can rely on Libvirt to provide this information since my changes to Libvirt got merged;
* Updated references to relevant OVN series;
* Added a section around potential future work based on the PCI device tracking in the placement service spec.

specs/xena/approved/transport-node-resou.message:
The idea here was:

* To associate CN RPs and TN RPs via an aggregate to avoid a parent-child relationship to address the multi-host scenario;
* Have an OVN Chassis RP (similar to the bw allocation spec here https://review.opendev.org/c/openstack/neutron/+/776701) under a TN RP since uplink interfaces (possibly bonded) will have limited bandwidth that will need to be shared across PFs/VFs exposed to all hosts. If PFs were tracked in the Placement service as resource providers, this would potentially give us a way to make requests such as: "give me a VF with this amount of bandwidth available via uplink ports of a SmartNIC".

Initially the goal of this whole structure was to be able to get a hostname of a SmartNIC for a via a serial number, for example:

1) A VF got allocated (by fulfilling a InstancePCIRequest);
2) A PCI VPD serial number got obtained from it (now we know which TN RP to look for);
3) An OVN chassis RP got looked up under the TN RP => the name of the OVN chassis RP is the SmartNIC hostname => this can be used as a hostname during port binding (could add a trait to the chassis RP for lookup purposes).
   * As discussed on IRC, it might be desirable to keep binding_host_id equal to the hostname of the hypervisor (http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/irclogs/%23openstack-nova/%23openstack-nova.2021-04-22.log.html#t2021-04-22T12:00:37) but let's see if that breaks anything at the Neutron side.

Why would we need to do such a lookup?

1) If Nova were to set binding_host_id to the hostname of the SmartNIC, it would need to know this information. A networking agent running on the SmartNIC needs to somehow make this information available to it while all relevant components (ovn-controller, Neutron, nova-compute) run in parallel and may come up at different times;

2) Alternatively, If Nova were to just pass binding_host_id==hypervisor_hostname plus the serial number and VF logical number during the port update to Neutron, the mechanism driver (OVN in this case) would then need too look up a hostname of the desired SmartNIC corresponding to the allocated VF based on the serial number.

We discussed doing (2) by having those associations stored in Neutron (not in Placement) on IRC http://eavesdrop.openstack.org/irclogs/%23openstack-nova/%23openstack-nova.2021-04-22.log.html#t2021-04-22T12:10:14.

Will consider what this might entail but it would be good to assess whether we need this RP structure for bandwidth allocation as well - might get mappings "for free" with this.

/PATCHSET_LEVEL.message:
This fixes integration on debian:

From cfc5615c20866566663ccd6abb92b996753638ad Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Dan Voiculeasa <dan.voiculeasa@windriver.com>
Date: Wed, 17 Nov 2021 15:47:31 +0200
Subject: [PATCH] Fix syslog-ng

Our Debian OS uses systemd-journal as the source.
Fixed illegal character, breaking the parser.

Signed-off-by: Dan Voiculeasa <dan.voiculeasa@windriver.com>
---
 syslog-ng-config/debian-source/syslog-ng.conf | 4 ++--
 1 file changed, 2 insertions(+), 2 deletions(-)

diff --git a/syslog-ng-config/debian-source/syslog-ng.conf b/syslog-ng-config/debian-source/syslog-ng.conf
index c4e7e07..56fb59a 100644
--- a/syslog-ng-config/debian-source/syslog-ng.conf
+++ b/syslog-ng-config/debian-source/syslog-ng.conf
@@ -63,7 +63,7 @@ options { chain_hostnames(off); flush_lines(0); use_dns(no); use_fqdn(no);
 # This is the default behavior of sysklogd package
 # Logs may come from unix stream, but not from another machine.
 #
-source s_src { unix-dgram("/dev/log"   ); internal();
+source s_src { systemd-journal(); internal();
                file("/proc/kmsg" program_override("kernel")   );
 };

@@ -161,7 +161,7 @@ destination d_newscrit   { file("/var/log/news/news.crit"); };
 destination d_newserr    { file("/var/log/news/news.err"); };
 destination d_newsnotice { file("/var/log/news/news.notice"); };

-# Some `catch-all' logfiles.
+# Some 'catch-all' logfiles.
 #
 destination d_debug    { file("/var/log/debug"); };
 destination d_error    { file("/var/log/error"); };
-- 
